Sep value was 315.323: https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIUFDNS315.323/285.507 = 1.1044 => 10.44% over 11 months so far.At this same rate, 12-month food inflation in Nov would be (1.1044^(12/11) - 1) * 100% = 11.44%. This is slightly lower than last month's analogous projection of 11.73% and slightly lower still than similar projections in previous months, which have been around 12%.Sep-Oct 22 mom inflation = (315.323/313.142 - 1) * 100% = 0.696%. Aug-Sep 22 mom inflation = 0.73%. Jul-Aug 22 mom inflation = 0.765%. In recent months before that, mom inflation has ranged from 0.99% to 1.14%. So mom food inflation has fallen substantially from its peak and continues to fall gently.
Correcting and error in my previous forecast. The calculations mistakenly were for if there were three months remaining and not two.

The Sept index value is 313.142 which is a MoM % increase of 0.7% from Aug at 310.875. The index needs to end above 314.06 to enter the "Between 10.0% and 12.5%" bucket. To exceed 12.5% we need to hit 321.20 and to hit 15% or more we need 328.33. That leaves us with the following required MoM % rates to get to each bin.

Aug's value was 310.875: https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIUFDNS310.875/285.507 = 1.0889 => 8.89% over 9 months so far.At this same rate, 12-month food inflation in Nov would be (1.0889^(12/9) - 1) * 100% = 12.03%. The past few months have seen similar projections, too.Jul-Aug 22 mom inflation = (310.875/308.532 - 1) * 100% = 0.76%. In recent months, mom inflation has ranged from 0.99% to 1.14%. So food inflation has started to decrease.If inflation continued at 0.76% mom for the rest of the forecast period, 12-month food inflation in Nov would be (1.0889*(1.0076^3) - 1) * 100% = 12.44% => 11.4%.

Updating based on today's number released for June 22. Pressures on food prices continue, and I don't expect them to resolve in the forecast period. I expect food inflation to continue at relatively similar mom rates over the coming months, with a slight decline primarily because of Fed actions. My forecast below is based on combining the 7-month inflation data available to date with a forecast for similar inflation in the remaining months of the forecast.

Updating since data from June '22 was released today: throughout the last six months the average increase in CPI was around 3.0 points - peaking to 3.3 in May, but it came back to 3.0 in June. At this rate, the answer should be 12.1%. It would take an average increase of 0.22 points a month to surpass 12.5% - which is possible, yet not that likely given the fact that most economies tend to stabilize after shocks.
In September I expect there will be media induced panic buying due to the poor harvest à la Feb/March 2020.
Reaffirming forecast until new data come out

I'm tilting my forecast a bit downward because of the Fed's rate hike. Before the rate hike, it seemed like the high end of bin 4 was most likely, but bin 5 was also very possible. I think the rate hike makes bin 4 most likely.

I've ended up in the same place as @belikewater. I think I was too influenced by the distribution of recent history, and weighing heavily enough the economic forces going forward for the rest of the forecast period.In short, Bins 1 and 2 seem out of reach. They would involved a massive reversal compared to what we've seen so far. Bin 5 seems too high, because it would require an acceleration of prices from here. We'll have to watch out for that. The recent months have been right around 1% MoM change and just under that so I'm weighing bin 4 heavier than bin 5.
Realistically, I don't see how food inflation can be brought to the equivalent of 0.65% mom for the next 6 months, which is what would be needed for bin 3. So I'm lowering my forecast on bin 3.

Following @belikewater 's reasoning, I used a linear model to estimate the average monthly increase for the Food CPI. Considering the last six months (Nov-21 to Apr-22) in average there is a 2.43-points monthly increase - and throughout this period the variable behaves pretty linearly (though there is a slight boost during the last three months, possibly due to the Russian invasion to Ukraine).

Fed has already shown an aggressive stance to slow the market, There has been a 3% rise so far this year and forecasts expect the CPI to flatten through the remainder of the year.

Food inflation seems to be outrunning general inflation and also seems less likely to come down as the factors in favour of general inflation coming down (supply chains easing, rate hikes if they work, ...) wouldn't affect food inflation as much as the negative factors (war in Ukraine, India's wheat situation https://www.aljazeera.com/economy/2022/5/24/inside-indias-policy-flip-flop-on-wheat-exports, ...) might push food inflation upwards.
